&gt; 1. Is it possible to add getter or setter straight to F.prototype

You have to add your methods to the prototype of the function itself.

You can keep using `Object.defineProperty` to do this if you have a specific reason to do so, but you can also just directly add the property to the prototype this way: 

```Car.prototype = { /* methods &amp; properties */ }```

Example:

&lt;!-- begin snippet: js hide: false console: true babel: false --&gt;

&lt;!-- language: lang-js --&gt;

    class Car {
      constructor(brand) {
        this.brand = brand
      }
      get brand() {
        if (this._brand) console.log(this._brand)
        else console.log(&quot;Don&#39;t forget to pick a car!&quot;)
      }
      set brand(value) {
        if (value == &quot;Tesla&quot;) this._brand = value
        else console.log(&quot;Choose another car&quot;)
      }
    }

    let car = new Car(&quot;BWM&quot;)

    function CarF(brand) {
      this.brand = brand
    }

    CarF.prototype = {
      get brand() {
        if (this._brand) console.log(this._brand)
        else console.log(&quot;Don&#39;t forget to pick a car!&quot;)
      },
      set brand(value) {
        if (value == &quot;Tesla&quot;) this._brand = value
        else console.log(&quot;Choose another car&quot;)
      }
    }

    let car2 = new CarF(&quot;BMW&quot;)

&lt;!-- end snippet --&gt;

Just in case you were curious, here&#39;s how you do it with `Object.defineProperty`. But it&#39;s a little more verbose having to do this for every property you want to add to the class. 

&lt;!-- begin snippet: js hide: false console: true babel: false --&gt;

&lt;!-- language: lang-js --&gt;

    function Car(brand) {
      this.brand = brand
    }

    Object.defineProperty(Car.prototype, &#39;brand&#39;, {
      get() {
        if (this._brand) console.log(this._brand)
        else console.log(&quot;Don&#39;t forget to pick a car!&quot;)
      },
      set(value) {
        if (value == &quot;Tesla&quot;) this._brand = value
        else console.log(&quot;Choose another car&quot;)
      }
    })

    const car = new Car(&quot;BMW&quot;)

&lt;!-- end snippet --&gt;

